    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-02-28T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-02-28T10:00:00-05:00" n="61"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d61">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7764: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-02-28T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >February 28, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 28—12:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>74. Dr. Yen, Chinese Ambassador, stated to me today that he had just received a
                    most private letter from Nanking which said that if the Japanese should attempt
                    to compel acceptance of their “three principles” by an ultimatum or if the
                    Japanese should advance into Shantung, General Chiang Kai Shek positively would
                    fight.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
